On September 21, 2017, Donald J. Trump hosted a working luncheon in New York with the leaders of Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Guinea, Namibia, Nigeria, Senegal, South Africa, and Uganda. The purpose of the meeting was to discuss how the United States and Africa can work together towards prosperity and peace. The leaders talked about a pragmatic strategy that focuses on security, infrastructure, economic development, and other common interests. They believe that this approach will help reduce terrorism and promote job growth for both Africans and Americans. They also addressed other global challenges, such as the threat from North Korea.